posts.name: Ryan Reed
posts.cooked:
Note on replacing the WAGOs: They can be pulled apart (it’s essentially a stack of them with an end cover) so if you desolder and remove them all, you can take the broken one apart and replace the lever with the lever from the new one you bought.

Desoldering all of them will be difficult, and also getting them back inside when you’re done. I recommend having plenty of solder wick and some lead-free solder. Diluting the lead-free solder with lead-free solder may make it easier to remove, though it’ll require multiple attempts. Solder flux can help the wick clear out the hole, allowing you to reinsert the repaired WAGOs.

Keeping the colors consistent should comply with R710M regulations.

posts.name: Brett B Bonner
posts.cooked: This channel cannot be utilized without repair. Several solutions exist based on whether it and the robot comply with competition standards. REV offers a PDH repair service for $110 plus shipping. Since only one of three PDH channels is faulty, the other two can power the Rio and radio, allowing additional components to be connected via a PDH channel if needed. A 10A or 20A breaker is required, and observing wire gauges is advised. If competition compliance isn't a concern, splitting a low-power output with Wago 221-413 can enable multiple functions on the same circuit. Lastly, the Limelight 3 operates within 4.1 to 16V, so it doesn't need the VRM; it can connect directly to a PDH or Mini Power Module circuit.

posts.name: Joseph Walters
posts.cooked: The text is: The Push-In Cage Clamp series will be looked up online the next morning but as per the datasheet, @AriMB mentioned the series below which states “Push-In Cage Clamp”. If the terminal is in the closed and locked position, it still should have push-to-seat capability. As others have mentioned, the terminal blocks are soldered to the PCB, which will take a lot of heat but is repairable with persistence and skill. Repair is the ultimate solution. However, in a pinch, you could strip the largest gauge wire that fits in that port, crimp a ferrule on the stripped end, and firmly PUSH the terminal into the port where it normally seats and is closed. You will have to overcome the spring force of the jaws but it is feasible and listed as one of the terminal insertion methods in the WAGO datasheet. Testing this method on one of ours a year and a half ago required a steady hand and a lot of force, though it worked well for insertion. For removal, consider making it a 8-inch or longer pigtail and using a WAGO221 in-line lever-loc as a temporary termination point while deciding on permanent repair or future use.

posts.name: philso
posts.cooked: As others have suggested, send your PDH to REV to be repaired properly. Board with large plane layers that act as heatsinks make desoldering very difficult with typical soldering irons and it is likely that one can damage the circuit board. Frequently, I have seen the boards damaged because the iron was held on the joint so long in an unsuccessful attempt to melt the solder, the fiberglass material delaminated. The worst is if one pulls a plated hole out because the iron was not hot enough. In the past, I have replaced the Wago and Weidmuller connectors using either the desoldering stations at work or using a high-power, high-thermal-mass soldering iron like the one shown below. I have also used it for desoldering difficult parts at my workplace when the regular soldering irons were not sufficient. One has to be quick to prevent damaging the board with excessive heat. I purchased mine at an antique radio swap meet but they are still made and sold.

posts.name: Chris Herzog
posts.cooked: The text is frequently damaged boards due to prolonged holding of iron near joints during attempts to melt solder. The fiberglass material often delaminates, and pulling a plated hole can occur if the iron isn’t hot enough. @philso is correct about the issue. Pulling a plated hole is particularly harmful on multi-layer boards as it may act as an interlayer. Not enough heat melts all solder, leaving residual solder which can cause problems. Using a larger, hotter iron is advised over smaller ones that lose heat to components. My experience with soldering includes using a robust iron to achieve quick and reliable solder joints. Heat damage occurs primarily from high temperature differences and prolonged contact. Maintaining proper technique prevents stress from expansion. Copper on PCB floats due to heat-sensitive adhesive, preventing lifting during soldering. @philso emphasizes the importance of sufficient thermal mass when soldering. Practice with scrap PCBs or salvaged parts improves skills.
